# Ambari MCP Server Configuration
# 1.Copy the example environment file:
   ```bash
   cp .env.example .env
   ```

# 2. Edit the `.env` file with your Ambari server details: 
# Ambari Server Configuration
AMBARI_BASE_URL=http://<your-ambari-server>/api/v1
AMBARI_USERNAME=<>
AMBARI_PASSWORD=<>
TIMEOUT_MS=30000
PORT=3333

# Instructions:
# 1. Replace 'your-ambari-server' with your actual Ambari server hostname or IP
# 2. Update AMBARI_USERNAME with your Ambari login username
# 3. Update AMBARI_PASSWORD with your Ambari login password
# 4. Save this file
# 5. Restart the MCP server to apply the new configuration

# Example configurations:
# AMBARI_BASE_URL=http://192.168.1.100:8080/api/v1
# AMBARI_BASE_URL=https://ambari.mycompany.com:8080/api/v1
# AMBARI_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8080/api/v1

# Security Note:
# Keep this file secure and do not commit it to version control
# as it contains sensitive credentials
